# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eliot-blackwelder
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:eliot-blackwelder/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] The **American Ornithological Society** (**AOS**) is an ornithological organization based in the United States.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] The society was formed in October 2016 by the merger of the American Ornithologists' Union (AOU) and the Cooper Ornithological Society.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Its members are primarily professional ornithologists, although membership is open to anyone with an interest in birds.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] The society publishes the two scholarly journals, *Ornithology* (formerly *The Auk*) and *Ornithological Applications* (formerly *The Condor*) as well as the *AOS Checklist of North American Birds*.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] The American Ornithological Society claims the authority to establish standardized English bird names throughout North and South Americas.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] In 2013, the American Ornithologists' Union (AOU) announced a collaboration with the Cooper Ornithological Society, streamlining operations through joint meetings, a shared publishing office, and a reorientation of their journals.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] By October 2016, the AOU ceased its independent status, merging with the Cooper Ornithological Society to establish the unified American Ornithological Society.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] The American Ornithologists' Union was founded in 1883.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Three members of the Nuttall Ornithological Club, Elliott Coues, J.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] The founding convention was held in the library of the American Museum of Natural History on September 26, 1883.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Founding members of the AOU include those present at the inaugural convention, listed below.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] In addition, the members of the new Union unanimously enrolled two others as founding members: Professor S.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Baird, who was unable to attend due to his duties at the Smithsonian, and J.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Allen, who could not attend due to physical disability.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] In 2013, the American Ornithologists' Union announced a close partnership with the Cooper Ornithological Society, including joint meetings, a centralized publishing office, and a refocusing of their respective journals to increase efficiency of research.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] In October 2016, the AOU announced that it was ceasing to operate as an independent union and was merging with the Cooper Ornithological Society to create the American Ornithological Society.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] In October 2023, the AOS announced that it was set to rename all bird species associated with individuals, aiming to eliminate names linked to figures with racist pasts.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Aiming for more descriptive names based on habitat or physical features, the renaming process would involve public input.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Over 100 avian species across the Americas would undergo this change, with the move eliciting mixed reactions within the birding community.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Regular membership in the AOS is open to any dues paying person with an interest in birds.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Student rates are available for full-time students.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] *Student Membership Awards* of a no-cost membership are available to qualified undergraduate and graduate students who wish to pursue a career in ornithology.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] The quarterly journal, *Ornithology* (formerly *The Auk*), has been published since January 1884.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] The quarterly journal, *Ornithological Applications* (formerly *The Condor*), has been published since 1899.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Other significant publications include the *AOS Checklist of North American Birds*, which is the standard reference work for the field, and a monograph series, *Ornithological Monographs*.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] The AOS presents annual awards to recognize achievements and service, support research, and encourage student participation.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] A decline in student membership in the AOU and other ornithological societies prompted creation of a *Student Affairs Committee* in 2003.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Several awards for students were created starting in 2005 as well as activities for students at annual meetings.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Much of the AOS's work is accomplished by its thirty-three standing committees.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Many of these are common for any organization such as Bylaws, History and Membership.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-ornithological-union] Other committees are of special importance to ornithology.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] Lawson was born on July 25, 1861, in Anstruther, Scotland.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] He moved to Hamilton, Ontario, Canada with his parents at age six.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] In 1883, he received his B.A. degree in natural science from the University of Toronto.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] He worked for the Geological Survey of Canada while pursuing his graduate degrees.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] He received his M.A. from the University of Toronto in 1885, and his Ph.D. from Johns Hopkins University in 1888.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] In 1890, he left the Geological Survey of Canada to work as a consulting geologist in Vancouver.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] In October of the same year, he accepted a position as assistant professor of Mineralogy and Geology at the University of California in Berkeley.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] He became a full professor in 1892, and a professor emeritus from 1928 to his death on June 16, 1952.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] Lawson was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1915, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1924, and the American Philosophical Society in 1925.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1926.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] He was a consulting geologist for the construction of the Golden Gate Bridge in the 1930s.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] His home in the La Loma Park area of the Berkeley Hills in Berkeley, California, called the "Andrew Cowper Lawson House" (1908), was especially designed for him by noted architect Bernard Maybeck to withstand earthquakes.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] The house is an official city designated Berkeley Landmark.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] The mineral Lawsonite is named for him, as is the Lawson Adit, originally a mining construction research tunnel on UC Berkeley's campus.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] 13,165 feet) in Sequoia National Park was officially named after him in 1976.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/andrew-lawson] 1,128 feet), located west of the Briones Hills in Contra Costa County, California, is named for him.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] He was born at Chicago, Illinois on June 4, 1880, the son of Isaac Simeon Blackwelder and Alice Gertrude née Boughton.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] Isaac was an insurance adjuster, then working on claims following the Great Chicago Fire of 1871.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] Alice was a former instructor at the University of Kansas.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] Eliot had an older brother, Paul Bruce Blackwelder, born in 1878.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] As a youth, Eliot developed an interest in entomology, and by the age of 15 he was a member of the American Ornithological Union.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] He matriculated to the University of Chicago, where he chose geology as his vocation, gaining an A.B in 1901.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] Immediately following graduation, he was invited by Rollin D.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] Salisbury to accompany him on an expedition to the Rocky Mountains.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] He would join Salisbury again in 1902 as a field assistant to explore glaciation in the Bighorn Mountains.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] Blackwelder received a fellowship at Chicago and became a geology instructor.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] From 1902–1903 he was a fellow then an assistant at the University of Chicago.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] In 1903–1904, he worked as a paleontologist on the Carnegie Institute expedition to China.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] He was one of the assistants to Bailey Willis, the leader of the expedition.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] The trip lasted more than a year, crossing Asia, northern China, and ending on the Yangtze River.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] Much of the region covered was unknown to Western geologists.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] It resulted in a four volume report, one of which was assembled by Blackwelder.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] After returning to America, on September 26, 1904, he was married to Jean Otis Bowersock, a childhood friend.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] The couple would have seven children: two sons and five daughters.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] He was offered a position as instructor at the geology department of the University of Wisconsin in 1905.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] During the following years he became assistant professor then associate professor in geology.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] Starting in 1906 he became associated with the United States Geological Survey.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] First he was an assistant geologist in Alaska and southeastern Wyoming during 1906–1908.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] After 1909 he worked as a geologist performing studies in northern Utah, southeastern Idaho, and western Wyoming.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] Most of his field work involved stratigraphic and glacial features of these regions, as well as their economic resources.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] In 1911, he co-authored an elementary textbook titled, *Elements of Geology*, with Harlan H.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] The same year he was named full professor at Wisconsin, and would remain at the university until 1916.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] In 1914 he was awarded a Ph.D. with a thesis titled, *Post-cretaceous history of the mountains of central western Wyoming*.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] From June 1916 until August 1916 he was head of the geology department at the University of Illinois.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] In 1917 he was a member of the California Petroleum Commission, having been appointed by the state governor, William D.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] During 1919 he was a visiting professor at Stanford University, where he taught for a quarter.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] He became the chief geologist for the East Butte Copper Mining Company in September 1919, remaining there until 1921.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] In 1921 he was lecturing at Harvard, taking the place of Reginald Aldworth Daly who was on leave.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] During 1921–1922, he partnered with Lewis A.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] Humphrey to establish the Teton Syndicate, where Blackwelder served as a manager.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] This trust was intended to locate and extract petro-minerals.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] In 1922, he was named full professor at Stanford University, filling the chair of the geology department to replace the retiring Bailey Willis.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] He would remain chair at Stanford until 1945.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] In 1936, Blackwelde was elected a member of the United States National Academy of Sciences, then he was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1939.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1940, after serving as Vice President in 1933 and 1939.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] He was elected President of the Seismological Society of America, serving from 1947 to 1949.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] During his time at Stanford, Blackwelder made geological explorations of the Sierra Nevada range and its glacial valleys.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] He explored the arid regions of the southwest, writing papers on the origins and evolution of desert landscapes.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] He was one of the first geologists to favor an impact origin for the Barringer Crater.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] After retirement, he served in the Palo Alto chapter of the Atlantic Union Committee.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] During the final years of his life, his body was weakened from Parkinson's disease.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] He died on January 14, 1969, surviving his wife by three years.
[src:eliot-blackwelder/eliot-blackwelder] The couple were able to celebrate their 60th wedding anniversary together.
